03917nam a22005535i 9780520951570DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20122012cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209515707 a10.1525/97805209515702doi  a(DE-B1597)519081  a(OCoLC)794493900  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBL2470.S6bC47 2016 7aREL0170002bisacsh04a200.9682231 aChidester, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWild Religion :bTracking the Sacred in South Africa /cDavid Chidester. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Going Wild -- t2. Mapping the Sacred -- t3. Violence -- t4. Fundamentalisms -- t5. Heritage -- t6. Dreamscapes -- t7. Purity -- t8. Power -- t9. World Cup -- t10. Staying Wild -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWild Religion is a wild ride through recent South African history from the advent of democracy in 1994 to the euphoria of the football World Cup in 2010. In the context of South Africa's political journey and religious diversity, David Chidester explores African indigenous religious heritage with a difference. As the spiritual dimension of an African Renaissance, indigenous religion has been recovered in South Africa as a national resource. Wild Religion analyzes indigenous rituals of purification on Robben Island, rituals of healing and reconciliation at the new national shrine, Freedom Park, and rituals of animal sacrifice at the World Cup. Not always in the national interest, indigenous religion also appears in the wild religious creativity of prison gangs, the global spirituality of neo-shamans, the ceremonial display of Zulu virgins, the ancient Egyptian theosophy in South Africa's Parliament, and the new traditionalism of South Africa's President Jacob Zuma. Arguing that the sacred is produced through the religious work of intensive interpretation, formal ritualization, and intense contestation, Chidester develops innovative insights for understanding the meaning and power of religion in a changing society. For anyone interested in religion, Wild Religion uncovers surprising dynamics of sacred space, violence, fundamentalism, heritage, media, sex, sovereignty, and the political economy of the sacred.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aCultszSouth Africa. 0aCultural pluralismzSouth Africa. 0aNativistic movementszSouth Africa. 0aReligion and sociologyzSouth Africa. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520951570423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520951570.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles